Apache Kafka is a distributed streaming platform that can be used to process real-time data streams. In the context of a real estate portal, it can be used to stream real-time data related to property listings, purchases, sales, and rentals. The data can be processed in real-time using Kafka Streams or KSQL to extract meaningful insights and trigger real-time actions based on specific events.

Here's a simple example of how you could use Kafka to stream property listing data:

1. First, you'll need to set up a Kafka cluster and create a topic for property listings.
2. Next, you'll need to write code to produce data to the property listings topic. This code will be responsible for sending the property listing data to the topic. For example, the code could be a REST API endpoint that accepts new property listings and sends the data to the topic.
3. On the consumer side, you'll write code to process the property listing data in real-time. This code could be a Kafka Streams application that performs real-time data processing on the stream of property listings. For example, the code could calculate real-time statistics on the average price of properties in a particular area, or perform fraud detection to prevent fake listings from appearing on the portal.

